The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic as early as this year.
Maybe
Perhaps the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is quite mature and our operators offer virtually all the services as their partners in Western Europe.
However, there is something missing – a virtual operator that forces traditional operators to lower the price.
Maybe it won't be long.
The fact that Czech operators belong to the most expensive in Europe we have already written many times on Mobil.cz.
In the end, it was also confirmed by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, who noted that the price of SMS is higher than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in regulating roaming rates, perhaps a paradoxical situation will be created - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS will cost less from abroad than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that would really want to start the fight.
Perhaps it sounds absurd, as we have three mobile networks and coverage well above 100%.
On the other hand, mobile telephony operators like to get tired of the fact that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this sense, the head of the Czech Telecommunications Council (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>) Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xA1>k often emphasises that in the past he has sometimes expressed that there is no room for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with its own network no longer likely has many possibilities. (Otherwise, it might be difficult to find other frequencies now).
But there is still another possibility - the virtual operator.
It is precisely the entry into the market of virtual operators that has led to a significant drop in prices, to which then traditional operators would have to react.
At the same time, even before sharks like Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile entered the market, similar voices resonated in Britain as we did.
It has been shown, however, that the place for such operators is there and that they can be really successful.
At the end of the day, we don’t have to go very far.
In February of this year we informed you of the arrival of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year this operator has managed to gain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time behind Mobilking lies the Penta financial group to which in the Czech Republic belongs, among other things, the U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on a much more concrete target group.
In order to actually function, it is enough for many fewer customers than for a traditional operator.
They do not carry behind, that is to say, relatively high costs for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
So in the world, virtual operators usually present themselves at low cost, they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often in balance with the offer of the most restricted services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS that cost at least half as much as its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can be a pretty good move even betting on a target group not recently.
This operator aims to say specifically about men.
“Real men choose a mobileking operator that they like and can be trusted with,” says David Seibertz, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which produces this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether we can affirm a similar concept as in Poland.
Vodafone press spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> said: "The Czech market is relatively small for a fragmented approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, from the point of view of services it is relatively saturated."
In the Czech Republic there is no possibility, mobile network operators say
But it seems almost certain that if there will ever be an operator in the Czech Republic it will not be Mobilking.
“We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not have much expectation.
Mobilking’s surge will happen rather in the other countries of our area,” Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>kov<0xC3><0xA1>, the spokesman for the Penta financial group, told Mobile.cz.
Thus, he indirectly confirmed that the current operators in the Czech Republic are not very much in favour of this idea.
Rather, they try to do everything because they don’t create any potential competitors.
For a while, it has not hidden its interest in starting a virtual operator, the GTS Novara group that would like to take another step to become a real competitor of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nika O2 in the field of corporate customers.
“We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed services but also mobile telecommunications.
And it's better before you do it.
We have repeatedly negotiated on this possibility with all Czech mobile network operators.
We have already been able to make progress in negotiations with some of them,” said Group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
Maybe there will be better times.
From unofficial information it turns out that the first virtual operator will probably have to have it by the end of the year.
For now, however, a impenetrable wall of silence stands around its creation.
“At the moment we do not believe that there is room in the Czech market for the creation of a fully qualified virtual operator.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
So far, no one with a complex and serious project has addressed us," Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> of the Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nika O2 press section said in his statement to Mobil.cz.
The other operators also rely on the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobil press spokesman Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> adds in a rare agreement with the O2 statement: "For now, we have not noticed any vital and advantageous commercial project for both, on which it is possible to continue to build."
He adds: “In the T-Mobile network, a virtual operator will hardly appear by the end of the year.
At this point we would have already had to have a concrete agreement on the table, so that it could be considered on the horizon."
Vodafone focuses its attention rather on achieving its 3G license requirements.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> adds: "We are open to negotiations by potential virtual operators, especially in the area of cost and infrastructure sharing.
We consider this, from the customer’s point of view, the most productive.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common network for fast mobile internet.”
Competent authorities - with complicit operators
The attitude of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to lower prices and thus to a decrease in profit.
Why then facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The annoyances surrounding the U:fon creation testify that when the operators hold on to something they know how to rest on the same side.
Perhaps the great pressure is pressing against <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> during the period of creation of U:fon towards the company of T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by public access information from the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> web pages.
But right now U:fon serves as a topic for which you do not accept the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> noted: “The environment of the mobile phone market competition has been little further enhanced with the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
