Especially when Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa adds: "Outside where virtual operators commonly work, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile phone services."
But, of course, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the lowering of prices do not belong to the interests of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
Truly shocking throughout the situation is the almost exciting harmony of these three operators resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence, you ask yourself.
Equally as the ‘same price of petrol for all petrol stations is undoubtedly the result of coincidence and competitive struggle.
"The section has found no signs of anti-competitive behavior regarding this fact and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No operator has a dominant position, so it has no corresponding greater responsibility for its market behavior.
The unnecessary tools for the opening of the mobile network market for virtual operators may also be missing from the telecoms regulator," Chalupa said in a statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets drawn up by <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>, according to which telecommunications are from the point of view of economic competition as the only market.
In such a market, of course, no Czech operator has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer another approach - for the creation of a virtual operator is always unnecessary the agreement of the network operator.
And the mobile operator has – at the end of the accounts logically – the monopoly of its network.
So for a certain portion it must be dominant by force.
But even if we do not accept this argument, for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS it should be an alarming minimum that three mobile operators behave in such a strangely similar way.
At the same time, complaints by the parties concerned (including the aforementioned GTS Novera company) show that during negotiations with all operators they encounter very similar obstacles.
Downloading responsibility to <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> in telecommunications is a fairly frequent trick with which <0xC3><0x9A>OHS is kept out of the whole thing.
