In a city apart, pride and processes of a black life
Hidden in the theme park on the suburbs of Orlando, a few miles away from the splendor, the noise, the huge, lies the quiet city where the pride and complications of the African-American experience come to life.
Eatonville, the first all-black city incorporated in the country and home to Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as it was described in 1935: "the city of five lakes, three croquet fields, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, plenty of guava, two schools and no prison."
It is now a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to show their respect for Hurston, the most famous writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
Yet in many ways, the city that has described – and that stops tourists from understanding it in the Florida tourist guide produced by the Depression-era Federal Writers’ Project – remains a place apart.
It’s as independent, dignified and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted sharing their thoughts with the white man, who “knowing so little about us, doesn’t know what’s being lost.”
Even now, in a year when a black presidential nominee, Senator Barack Obama, was called for an opening speech on the race, many here remain defiant from the outsider’s gaze.
“We’re very careful about how our story is told,” said 59-year-old Hortense Jones, a lifelong resident and member of the city’s oldest church.
"It must be right."
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and difficulty.
It is both a historical model of black power taking and a community of almost 2,400 where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a literary center but also an example in the shadow of the oaks of the rural culture of southern blacks - sometimes disgruntled, sometimes rewarded - born of American slavery.
Not surprisingly, residents here are both proud and protective.
And the concern for Eatonville's imagination really started with Zora, who everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced the world to her hometown through sincere, dialect-rich books, such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs of Florida’s leadership transformed the city, just off Route 17, a road that runs through the often forgotten center of Florida into a scenario of black history and human drama.
Low as a shell in both life and literature, Hurston brought readers to the store owned by Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then diverted to more private areas.
“Outside the road to the left,” he wrote, “is the modern public school, brown with its white finishes, with its well-kept and courtyarded gardens, which Howard Miller always knew, thinking he could barely read and write.”
She also mentioned the new husband of the widow Dash and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and whatever suits the passage rooms".
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston connected Eatonville with self-government but also with illiteracy, second marriage and sex.
Clearly, this was not Fodor's.
In fact, it was not a portrait that everyone appreciated.
“Now she was saying it the way it was,” said 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of Johnson’s girls who Hurston immortalized by citing men singing coarse songs about their beauty.
He adds: "Some people don't like it."
Hurston is still remembered here as a lively eccentric who often returned from his family moved to Jacksonville, Fla.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalls that when Hurston was floating in the city, he usually arrived unannounced in a triumphant Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants in a city that still boasts decent clothing today.
Many residents were fascinated, says Mr. Franklin, while others were drowning.
“People were always very happy to see Zora,” Mr. Franklin said.
But, she added, leaning on her patio chair on the back above Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "she never stayed long."
When Hurston died in 1960, he was poor and his books had gone out of print.
Along with the rest of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten her.
Although once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in a unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Fla., where she had lived.
In Eatonville, there were no major commemorative ceremonies, and no major conferences.
"I don't think they understand his contribution to the world or his abandonment to everyone," said Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows," a Hurston biography published in 2003.
A change took place in the 1980s.
Orange County officials wanted to put a five-lane highway across the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the two-lane main road.
The expansion of Orlando has already pushed Interstate 4 across the western border of the city.
The proposal came when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to the relative idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the battle over racial mixing brought hatred to the community’s doorstep.
“During that period, a group of white boys came and threw oranges and things at the people sitting on one side,” Mr. Franklin says.
“We actually had a girl who was killed by that one once.
They threw a coward out of a car."
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston made a request to the Supreme Court for forced integration, defining his decision in Brown against the school office "an insult rather than an honor for my race".
Residents now say that the disintegration of schools, despite having been positive in some respects, dilute Eatonville’s cohesion and jeopardizes the confidence of its youth.
“The black kids were used to being hugged — I remember this — hugging your teacher in the morning, hugging your teacher in the evening,” said N. Y. Nathiri, Ella Dinkins’ daughter and the executive director of Preserve the Eatonville Community, a non-profit group.
This lasted, he added, until the teachers and students came from the same place.
“You didn’t embrace your white teacher because your white teacher—I mean, there’s a cultural division there,” said Mrs. Nathiri.
Civil rights, however, helped and created space for many other Zora Neale Hurstons - black writer, actress and artist who overcame prejudices, as she did, with happy self-confidence and lines like: "How can some deny themselves the pleasure of my company!
I just can't figure it out."
In 1975, writer Alice Walker began a long journey to Hurston's unmarked grave and began to fight for the resurrection of her reputation.
Five years later, an acclaimed biography of Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway struck the shelves of the bookstores, reintroducing it into the American canon.
The highway project arrived just as his most famous daughter had once again turned on the lights of the hill.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The community began designing in 1988 a festival dedicated to Hurston to show what could ruin the state with its highway.
Thousands of fans came to the inaugural event two years later, and every January, many return for the commemoration.
Many years later, the state withdrew from its road project.
“The five lanes of the resurfaced highway brought what would be called high speed, a real pride for the city,” said Ms. Nathiri.
Mrs. Boyd puts it more simply: "Now she saved Eatonville."
The victory over the highway project has helped change the image that the city has of itself.
Those out of town like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who began coming to church here in 1993, began to appear in large numbers, and residents began to reevaluate the past.
Eatonville joined the public historical record in 1998.
A new one-story library (called Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on a refurbished and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains an anomaly of Florida: just six miles from downtown Orlando, it can give the feeling of a secondary road under the summer rain, as small as when it was founded with just 27 black families in the 1980s.
(It's 90 percent black today.)
Outsiders who come to look for the story of Eatonville, for its meaning, are often still treated with caution.
A permission requested in advance is required for most of the interview, to some things - like the murals on Eatonville's oldest church, painted by a white man, that show black men in the fields - do not have permission to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, such as Ms. Jones, a fat teacher, with a weakness for bright red, still fear that their island community will be misunderstood.
Yet, as soon as the Hurston festival expanded, a high level of citizen pride also emerged.
Young people, in particular, tend to see Eatonville with Hurston seeing his entire race: beautiful, problems and everything, not better, not worse and proud, creative, great worker, silly and confused like other races and ethnic groups in America.
It is sincere civic affection that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin’s grandson, Edwin Harvey, 18, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the local government or for the Police Department, who said he may need help.
And even those who are younger, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, 11-year-old twins from Winter Park, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
“Many people, if they just walked in here, will think, ‘Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others,’” said Alondra Kenon after the rally on a recent Sunday.
“But if you really stop and take a moment to look at history, it’s really a pretty city.”
