The Ministry of the Interior requires drivers with three administrative penalties for excessive blood alcohol, to install in their car a system that prevents the vehicle from driving in a state of intoxication or if it does not blow in the appropriate device.
The measure was announced last June and is already included in the annual report of the Prosecutor General’s Office, according to which it will be a one-year pilot project.
The purpose of this project is the reintegration of the driver, since this will have to attend a rehabilitation course on the road.
In addition to the General Prosecutor for Road Safety, the Directorate-General for Traffic (DGT) and the Fondazione Istituto Tecnologico para la Sicurezza dell’Automobile (FITSA) will participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of drivers reported more than once per drunk driving then drive the car again.
The alcoholock would prevent it, because it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the rate of alcohol in the expired air and prevents the car from being put into motion if the driver does not breathe, or when a higher concentration of alcohol is detected than allowed.
The cost is more than 1000 euros and would be in charge of the fine.
In this regard, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles fitted with such devices can reduce up to 65% of the infringements committed during the first year of introduction.
And in Spain it is estimated that it could save the lives of 115 people a year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to stop these behaviors before they become criminal offences.
And to facilitate its development, since the legal reform can be carried out on an ordinary basis, and, without doubt, the necessary reform for the criminal procedure would require an organic law.
However, the device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial solution, although it has already been introduced experimentally in some industrial and public vehicles.
Just tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on a PSOE initiative in which it intends to install this system in school buses, as has already been done in France.
