Talking in Sleep
Some children talk during the night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very agitated to tell us something that happened to them the day before, but to those children who talk while they are asleep.
The first time it happens, you take a scare, but it doesn’t really matter much.
This is a benign alteration of sleep called somniloquium.
It manifests with a certain frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Surely, most of you have been told that you had spoken in your sleep.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (once in life, for example, associated with an episode of high fever) or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once a month...), the day after the baby remembers nothing.
There is no single reason that can explain this phenomenon.
Sometimes there are episodes associated with other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night terrors, nighttime enuresis (making the pipe in bed), or sleepwalking, but not necessarily so.
As already mentioned above it can be associated with very high fever stages, stress or overexertion situations.
In any case, it is a phenomenon yet little studied.
The intensity with which it appears is also extremely variable.
It can happen that the person speaks with a very quiet tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper or that the opposite happens (cries, screams, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, it would be advisable to look at the child and eventually consult a specialist to check if there are any issues that are generating an abnormal state of anxiety as a result of the situation.
We have said that this is a benign alteration so there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (for example, if paired with insomnia or a stressful situation).
What you can do, on the other hand, is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to over-excited the child before he goes to sleep.
Propose quiet games and avoid programs or television series that arouse fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children for whom it is difficult to relax, you can use relaxation techniques to help them gain some inner calm.
This will allow the child to sleep more comfortably.
Once the sleepwalkers appear, try to keep calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember anything of what happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him.
It is useless, because he is not aware of what is happening, and you would interrupt his sleep.
Although he's talking, he's sleeping and so he's resting.
Remember that if it appears very anxious and the episodes have a certain frequency it is better to consult a doctor or check from where such a great anxiety arises in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not the most common situation), don’t fall into the temptation of asking him a question to get information.
You will get nothing, because he is asleep and therefore not conscious to organize his thought.
In addition, you are able to hear what he says but not see what he is dreaming of saying it, so you need to pay a lot of attention to the interpretation of the information and the conclusions that these could lead to.
Never tell your child that you could ask him questions during the night to know his or her secrets.
Not even for fun.
Something like that causes a huge amount of anxiety.
In short, don't worry, it's nothing serious, it's an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
