The encounter - The blood is safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated the tenth anniversary of its foundation yesterday, and its president, Dr. FrancineDécary, had every reason to rejoice, as Héma-Québec became one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, it has regained the public’s trust, seriously shaken by the blood scandal infected in the years between 1980 and 1990.
As we know, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected with the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980s.
Faced with such drama and population protests, the Government of Canada conducted in February 1994 a public inquiry, led by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to spread recommendations to prevent the recurrence of such a disaster.
While Judge Krever was late in drawing up a report, some provinces set up a committee with the aim of designing a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the Gélineau et Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to supply Quebec and the Société canadienne du sang (Canadian Blood Society) to all other provinces and two territories.
In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its activities, just 38% of people declared that they still had confidence in the donation system in Quebec, recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was mortifying.
Thanks to ongoing efforts to improve the safety of blood samples and field research over the following years, we have regained the public’s trust,” he explains before saying proudly that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of Quebec’s population now had confidence in Hema-Quéc.
However, Dr. Décary is convinced that "trust is something extremely fragile".
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were many cases of the human variant of mad cow in Europe, a new manifestation of the disease of Creutzfeldt-Jakob, which has been in the presidency since 1998, the year of its foundation.
“And we didn’t know at all whether that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
It was based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports, according to which when you have doubts and could achieve a serious disease, in this case the disease of Creutzfeldt-Jakob that manifests itself with a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, are taken measures of exclusion.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than a month in the UK since 1980 was refused.
Now, for a few years, it has been shown that without any doubt this disease is transmitted through infected blood.
This episode has shown us so much that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle.”
In 1999, a much more efficient technique for the detection of HIV appeared on the market: nucleic acid (TAN) tests that allow to recognize directly in the blood of donors the presence of the virus and not that of antibodies against it, on which the tests used until then were based.
TANs have reduced the window period, i.e. from the moment the person contracted the disease to the one where the first viruses can be detected in the blood thanks to our techniques, explains the specialist.
It was possible to reduce that period to a duration of less than a week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and therefore not being able to identify them has decreased significantly.
These improvements have made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of contracting AIDS with a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
In other words, this means that it will be necessary to distribute 12 million blood samples before someone gets infected with the HIV virus.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood samples each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmitted with a transfusion is found.
I believe that today one can feel calm in receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health, says the head of the management of Héma-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to keep our products safe.
It is never known which pathogen will emerge in the system.
No later than a year ago, the Chikungunya virus appeared on Réunion Island, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted in the blood by an insect.
We must be constantly vigilant", Dr. Décary continues before stressing that in addition to having safe resources, Héma-Québec must also provide sufficient resources.
“Needs are increasing as the population ages.
Being the most aggressive cancer treatment, patients often need a supply of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences for the number of donors, which on average makes up only 3% of Quebec’s residents acceptable as donors.”
However, all healthy people who have reached the age of 18 and meet the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer themselves as donors are not accepted, because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where the latter is widespread, they will be rejected for a period of one year.
“With this 3% we are able to maintain an inventory capable of meeting the needs of hospitals.
Cases of penury are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this group of donors as they age and can no longer make donations.
It is now difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to hold them back and encourage them to become regular donors.
Today, life is so frantic that it’s hard to find an hour to donate blood,” says desolate Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec not only distributes blood samples, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, ocular globe heart valves and skin that is used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being deposited at the Héma-Québec which manages the only public blood bank of umbilical cord in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, there is abundant blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the banking of our 1,000th cord blood sample and expect to pick up more than 1,000 each year.
You should start proposing them for transplants at the beginning of next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes this practice of cord blood removal as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot access you", as Héma-Québec does not have the necessary means to propose this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
