In the September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from M. Patrick J. Garver, vice president of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Pursuing an Orwellian logic, the latter states that the world’s largest gold company has played a defamation lawsuit by six million against three authors and a small publishing house quashed with the intention of launching a “transparent public debate”.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of a defamation lawsuit, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this substantial difference is completely hidden from Garver.
Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to bring to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his own.
No matter the outcome of the process, the writers and publisher of the book Canada Black will have to spend a large sum of money in order to organize their own defense and fight, with weapons you will definitely learn, against an army of lawyers funded by the mine company’s practically fund-free pockets.
