If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it is up to the public to present their own view of the facts.
Contrary to what happens in many countries where Barrick Gold works, in Canada debates are usually held with the exchange of views and not with manganese shots.
It would therefore be sufficient for the company to open its books, its documents, and establish a genuine debate, through newspapers, media, publications and the funding of independent research teams that could shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to have too much confidence in public opinion and mispronounces petitions and letters in support of the authors of Black Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can ask for a "public" debate when his contempt for the same public is well evident?
