In a democratic system, even the denigrates have the right to speak.
What Barrack Gold doesn’t understand – or doesn’t want to understand – is that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Canada Black does so primarily because it rejects the brutal means adopted by the mining company.
This audience is ready to listen to Barrick and to judge, but on the basis of civil exchanges of opinion, and not in view of what many perceive as a kind of squabbling (researching the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just given the authors of Canada an ultimatum that is intimate to them)
Beyond Garver’s surreal discourse, Barrack Gold’s squabbling is a direct attack on the freedom of university research and the pursuit of truth, indispensable in every democratic society.
