If in a country like Canada it is impossible to study and discuss uncomfortable topics at the world’s wealthiest companies, regret multiple lawsuits, who can do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do so by following the scientific rules as the authors of Black Canada do.
You have a right to reply.
For a long time, the university environment, of which we are part, has been able to manage debates and disagreements and to resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s excessive measures clearly show that, contrary to its claims, it does not seek a transparent debate at all.
This is at the expense of the university world, as is the case with the same public debate in Canada, and it is now time for governments to take measures to limit abusive lawsuits.
