The psychology of bidding in excess: why spend more money?
At auctions, buyers are likely to spend more, to overvalue the goods.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York have been able to discover the neuro-economic foundations of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, men don’t want to stay behind in a race like the eBay auction, so they’re willing to pay even a higher price.
The research sought to trace the nervous pattern of this "partition" at the level of the nervous system through experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played at the lot, the other group of players participated in a auction while with the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) method they examined the active areas of the brain of the people participating in the experiment.
In both games participants could win money, but in the auction game, where the substantial element is to bid more than the other, the body stretched under the cerebral cortex comes into play intensively when you lose the game.
This brain area, in addition to other functions, plays a role in the “self-gratification” mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the rise in price is explained by scanning the vehement reaction of the striated body.
To support their theory, the economists of the research group conducted a financial follow-up investigation.
In this survey, three groups tendered against a partner under different conditions.
The control group reported the actual value of the product in question and they made their bet.
In addition to this, they promised that in the event of a win they would receive another prize of $15.
The third group would instead have received $15 before the auction, but the group members would have lost the money in the event of a loss to the auction.
The difference between the two groups was that for one of them was highlighted the win, while for the other the loss.
By checking the neuroscientists' hypothesis, the members of the group playing "against loss" were willing to make higher bets than the control group or "winning".
