Hepatitis: when to see a doctor?
Almost half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, but in Hungary, among the first causes of death, chronic liver disease is mentioned.
In Hungary, the number of patients with hepatitis amounts to one hundred thousand, of which only 7,000 are treated: the reason is that many patients do not know they are infected.
The definition of hepatitis is the collective name of infectious liver diseases caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between the symptoms, typical are hepatitis and itterial, but their pathogens and diseases caused differ from one another.
Hepatitis viruses are spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen: Hepatitis A and E through the food channel (e.g. water and infected foods), Hepatitis B, C, D and other blood-borne viruses and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal discharge, saliva).
For those who travel it is useful to get vaccinated against the virus A and B, against C there is no vaccine.
Hepatitis A symptoms appear two to three weeks after eating infected foods, accompanied by general malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After yellow spots are formed on the skin and on the white of the eyes, the stool become clear and the dark urine, the healing takes place within two to three weeks.
One million people die every year worldwide from hepatitis B, the most serious variant of the disease, which causes liver cancer and liver cirrhosis.
The main reason is, according to estimates, that only one in ten people receives a pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if not treated it can cause liver cirrhosis and liver cancers.
Most infected people do not know they have contracted the disease because pathogens subdolely destroy liver cells, in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, it is very important to prevent and carry out regular medical tests.
This disease is much more common than the average in three groups: those who had a blood transfusion before 1991, addicts and tattoos.
In the world today, the number of people infected with chronic hepatitis C virus stands at 200 million.
Because even a routine laboratory examination reveals the disease is worth addressing your family doctor when you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
Recognized in time the disease is curable, the virus can be eliminated from the body, so the infectious power ceases and the formation of tumors can be prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, organized for the first time in 2004 worldwide by associations of patients.
The aim is to draw attention to viral chronic hepatitis, the causes of its development and the early recognition of the disease.
