What could be the best way to develop anti-collision technologies if it does not mimic the obstacles sensors that are found in nature?
For example, bees.
In the surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the calibers gave Nissan engineers the initial strategic clue as to how to build the next generation of anti-collision systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the BR23C biomimetic robot, a robotic mini-car with bee properties, with the ultimate goal of creating a system capable of scanning all collisions.
Flying bees form their own oval personal space that is very similar to our protective shield - explained to the exhibition Kazuhiro Doi, director of PR technology and research and development.
Important is the role of the bee’s view, capable of a 300-degree view in each direction.
The engineers came up with the telemetric laser idea to copy the function of the bee's view.
The BR23C detects obstacles up to two meters away within a 180-degree radius, calculates the distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor that immediately turns it into a command to avoid collision.
In a fraction of a second the robot perceives the obstacle and then, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes direction by turning the wheels to the measure necessary to avoid the accident.
This avoidance maneuver, unlike the current system, takes place in a completely instinctive manner.
“If it weren’t for that, the robot car wouldn’t be able to react quickly to avoid collisions,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robot car project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology corresponds to the damaging and more internal layer of the protective shield, within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to avoid the other bees.
This process must take place in a blink of an eye.
But unlike bees, the deviation cannot go upwards or downwards or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and in the direction of steering of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities available to bees to scan the other bees, the robot, as the possibility available, can rotate on itself, accelerate and slow down.
The BR23C is powered by lithium polymer batteries, lighter and high energy density, which means that their lifespan is higher than that of lithium ions.
According to Andoh, the instantity of the intelligent reaction is important, not the processing of data or even less the ability to store them.
This robot needs to process some inputs in a few seconds and react.
There is no need to store them and react with intuitive logic based on previous maneuver data, so use only a few tens of Kb memory.
There is no need for a memory of gigabytes or megabytes.
This is the first step towards the development of a technology for the immediate avoidance of collisions, which Nissan predicts will be able to be installed on standard vehicles within 10 years.
Additional application possibilities can be represented by unification with the GPS satellite navigation system which by avoiding obstacles on the road leads to destination.
