The Elites in Danger
The phenomenon had already emerged a few days ago with the vote of the House of Representatives against the $700 billion bailout plan launched by the White House: a significant portion of Americans were, and are, more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is confirmed by the New York Times yesterday informing us that the ongoing crisis is breaking the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old soul East Coast, moderate, favorable to federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul, on the other hand, conservative, hostile to “those of Washington” and to the financial center.
The soul, by the way, that has become too powerful alive with the vote I said at the beginning.
This just mentioned, however, is just an example of the changes, of the great changes, which the ongoing economic earthquake may pre-announce or already let you see: not only in the United States but throughout the West and perhaps not here alone.
Both in the US and Europe, the crisis seems to act as an accelerator of incubation phenomena for a long time, and in the new climate they solidify and finally come to light.
The first of these phenomena is the re-upgradation, the extraordinary re-launch, of the dual category of State-sovereignty in relation to a kind of re-nationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking and financial institutions, which, yes, have strong ties with abroad, but which, above all, see the balance sheets of people and families living in a single country, in a single state.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those people and families who, among other things, are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems essentially out of the question or not to have much to say: the flashy evidence is given by the European Union which divides as usual between the different interests and between the different state strategies fails to decide any common policy line.
And so it is from the government of every single state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all the provision of funds: since when it comes to the straits it is only the states that have economic resources, the mass of financial resources that can try to put things back in order.
They also have the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of incommensurable value, in certain circumstances, which probably no market and no international organisation will ever have in common.
This new emphasis that the crisis puts on the national-statutory element is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the growing importance that the latest developments in the economy tend to attribute to a factor very closely linked to that element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we were now entering the realm of network, of increasingly sophisticated technology, of immaterial, while we were convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we realized from a stretch that our future will have to do little to grow.
All things that, look a little, can certainly be transported from one place to the other of the earth but are nevertheless absolutely linked to a circumscribed space, to a territory.
So that those who find themselves to be sovereign, certainly possess many more cards than those who are not, those who have the misfortune of living in a place without harvest, without oil and without water.
I come to the second novel that predicts a fracture.
Whoever says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this regard, the economic crisis seems to produce two convergent phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective needs authoritative leadership, the request of someone who knows how to handle the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leaderships, especially economic ones, turns out to be so inadequate and full of shadow zones.
And together, something even deeper and in a certain way disturbing: a discredit, an intolerance, an image of inadequacy, a sense of distance, which tends to involve the entire ruling class in an increasing number of Western countries.
That is, it seems to be becoming more and more popular, in large areas of the population, the conviction that before their actions are the same ideas of the social elites so far in the limelight, their way of feeling and being, their culture in the overall acceptance of the term, to have made their own time and to be increasingly alien to the opinions of the majors.
The demand for leadership, in short, subterraneanly feeds a branched but powerful movement of delegitimization of the ruling classes and traditional political structures, which manifests itself in the sudden electoral "revolts" or in the sudden movements of the collective moods of these last and last times, from the British to the Croats, from the British to the Austro-Bertians, from the Croatsians to the Croats.
One has the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their formats would say someone, make it more and more difficult to understand, and therefore to represent, what is not now taking shape in the deep layers of the economy of Western societies.
In the face of all this, talking about a “mass rebellion” on the agenda would be frankly exaggerated.
