Krugman is one of the biggest critics of the Bush administration’s economic and foreign policy choices.
A few months after the September 2001 attacks, in the days when Enron failed, Krugman had predicted in an editorial published in the New York Times that the second event would be more decisive than the first, in terms of consequences on U.S. history.
A prediction that sparked not a few controversies and that for years was re-enacted to the economist, but that now turned out to be accurate.
“I’m surprised and also a little shocked by the speed with which the memory of scandals like the collapse of Enron or Worldcom disappeared from public attention,” Krugman said at the end of 2002.
According to Lorenzo Bini Smaghi, of the European Central Bank’s executive committee, Krugman is a “high-value economist,” but also a publicist with a “very aggressive style, particularly critical of the Bush administration’s excesses of liberalism.”
