Goodbye old cinema Paradise, the cities cancel the historic rooms
Historical cinemas close in favor of the Multiplex.
“A city without movie theaters is a blind city, it’s like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively photographs what is happening in the big Italian urban centers but also in the cities of the province.
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth on the periphery of large multi-seaters and the consequent death by consumptive mono-seaters in the central areas of cities, is one of those events that we find inevitable and incontrovertible but also has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
To disappear are often historical places and loaded with memory,"it is as if there were less a friend, a acquaintance with whom we shared a piece of street and many emotions", observes the director of Nuovo cinema Paradiso, the film that twenty years ago won Tornatore the Oscar and the Grand Prix of the jury of Cannes, for a film that won the Oscar and the Grand Prize of the jury.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of performers, speak clearly: in the last five years they have closed the beatings of 316 traditional cinemas, and to pay the most are the rooms in the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin.
Among the regions most affected by the closures is Emilia-Romagna with 82 cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And to demonstrate that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, these are the three Italian regions that have recorded the largest number of new multi-room cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany and in Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian exercise has developed irrationally" observes Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, "it is useful that new structures are being built but it would be necessary to ensure the survival of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all of its visitors are willing to move into the multiplexes.
Not to mention the lack of funding for the fund in favour of the operators: the state's previous debt is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful, from an ethical and moral point of view, that the Government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector, they would need between 16 and 18 million euros a year.”
Interestingly, the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried about the closures, decided to run to the stands with the signing of a protocol between the Municipality and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to protect and promote mono-sala cinemas both in the historical center and on the outskirts.
Among the rules provided are tax relief measures in favour of the operators and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: viewers will be able to enter the restricted traffic area and will have special rates for the stop and in some parking lots.
“It is an initiative that I like,” observes Giuseppe Tornatore, “and I hope that other cities follow the example of Bologna by setting other measures.
It is certain, however, that in order to counteract the rapport of multiplexing, traditional rooms also need to improve the quality of sound and image, because the public today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Supercinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New Paradise Cinema", which I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years, and when I walk in front of the Rialto or the Quirinale National road now closed, where I have lived so many shared emotions, so as not to see the signs torn by dust I turn the other way.”
