When energy is born from the waves now descend into the field the big
It is an extinct field, which occupies more than 70% of the planet’s surface and is now being discovered by the world’s largest energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources on which they have put their eyes, and now they are trying to put their hands, colossal like the Chevron.
The possibility of obtaining energy from sea movements has been studied for hundreds of years and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now environmentalist instances and the new increase in oil give impetus to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15 percent of the world’s electricity needs could be covered by offshore wind turbines.
This amount would be twice as much as that currently produced by nuclear power plants.
And there would be currents and tides.
Colossus at the attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a plant in northern Portugal.
When the agreement was announced, it seemed like a revolutionary step.
Two years away from betting on marine energy, there are more and more of these companies that have always been committed to traditional energy.
"Chevron is studying ocean energy technologies - said the spokesman of a company associated with the U.S. oil giant in the Wall Street Journal - and is considering the possibility of cooperating with us."
The cooperation in question concerns obtaining a permit from the U.S. Energy Commission, which is needed to launch a marine energy exploitation project in Alaska.
It’s a signal not long ago, especially if you consider that just in Alaska the US continues to extract oil and recently President Bush has launched a plan for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, there are New York’s Verdant Power Inc. and New Jersey’s Ocean Power to follow the path of energy coming from the sea and the amounts invested so far, as far as is not known in detail, indicate an increasing interest, according to observers.
Technology to be developed.
Experts talk about a technology still at dawn, also because marine energy does not escape all doubts about the environmental impact.
For now, plants such as the Portuguese or some in Scotland are small in size and do not seem to create major problems for the ecosystem.
In order to produce energy on a large scale, however, technologies with a greater environmental impact must be used.
And the choices are different: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys connected to each other.
The wave thrust, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure by pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure rotates a turbine that in turn feeds a generator.
Electricity is sent to shore through submarine cables.
For now, there are four such installations under design, pending only federal approval and part of the energy could serve for a military installation.
The Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces power for a shopping mall and a parking lot using six underwater turbines in the East River of New York.
The movement of water when there are tides causes the turbine blades to rotate, creating a rotational movement that feeds a generator.
Verdant said it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to take advantage of the energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say to the Institute for the Research of Electricity, is now worth the potential of the tides.
Although this is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable than the wind, the sun or the waves and therefore more reliable as an energy source.
It is precisely on the energy of the tides that states such as New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others overlooking the coasts, have already invested 7 and a half million dollars in 2008 and predicted investments up to 35 million for 2009.
